  "research_html": "<div class=\"research-section\">\n<p class=\"research-text\">Scythinus of Teos was an obscure iambic poet known only from later sources. His work, the <strong>Epigrams</strong>, is lost and survives in a single fragment. The primary source, Diogenes Laertius, reports that Scythinus attempted to render the philosophy of Heraclitus into verse. The sole surviving line, quoted by Diogenes Laertius, illustrates the work&#x27;s didactic purpose: &quot;One thing, the only truly wise, does and does not consent to be called by the name of Zeus.&quot; This indicates the epigrams versified core Heraclitean doctrines, such as the unity of opposites and the cosmic Logos, reinterpreting the nature of the divine governing principle through a philosophical lens. The work is transmitted exclusively through fragmentary quotations in doxographical sources. Diogenes Laertius provides the one extant line, and the Byzantine <strong>Suda</strong> encyclopedia also mentions Scythinus as a poet who versified Heraclitus but offers no additional text. Scythinus represents a minor tradition of philosophical didactic poetry aimed at popularizing complex thinkers. His historical significance lies primarily as a named example of the posthumous reception and interpretation of Heraclitus&#x27;s thought.</p>\n</div>",
  "rows": [
    {
      "kind": "text",
      "reference": "book 22.1.1",
      "text": "Ἦλθέν μοι μέγα πῆμα, μέγας πόλεμος, μέγα μοι πῦρ,",
      "witness_prefix": "",
      "speaker": null
    },
    {
      "kind": "text",
      "reference": "book 22.1.2",
      "text": "Ἰλισὸς πλήρης τῶν ἐς ἔρωτ’ ἐτέων,",
      "witness_prefix": "",
      "speaker": null
    },
    {
      "kind": "text",
      "reference": "book 22.1.3",
      "text": "αὐτὰ τὰ καίρι’ ἔχων ἑκκαίδεκα καὶ μετὰ τούτων",
      "witness_prefix": "",
      "speaker": null
    },
    {
      "kind": "text",
      "reference": "book 22.1.4",
      "text": "πάσας καὶ μικρὰς καὶ μεγάλας χάριτας",
      "witness_prefix": "",
      "speaker": null
    },
    {
      "kind": "text",
      "reference": "book 22.5.1",
      "text": "καὶ πρὸς ἀναγνῶναι φωνὴν μέλι καὶ τὸ φιλῆσαι",
      "witness_prefix": "",
      "speaker": null
    },
    {
      "kind": "text",
      "reference": "book 22.5.2",
      "text": "χείλεα καὶ τὸ λαβεῖν ἔνδον ἀμεμπτότατον.",
      "witness_prefix": "",
      "speaker": null
    },
    {
      "kind": "text",
      "reference": "book 22.5.3",
      "text": "καὶ τί πάθω; φασὶν γὰρ ὁρᾶν μόνον· ἦ ῥ’ ἀγρυπνήσω",
      "witness_prefix": "",
      "speaker": null
    },
    {
      "kind": "text",
      "reference": "book 22.5.4",
      "text": "πολλάκι τῇ κενεῇ Κύπριδι χειρομαχῶν.",
      "witness_prefix": "",
      "speaker": null
    },
    {
      "kind": "text",
      "reference": "book 232.1.1",
      "text": "Ὀρθὸν νῦν ἕστηκας, ἀνώνυμον, οὐδὲ μαραίνῃ,",
      "witness_prefix": "",
      "speaker": null
    },
    {
      "kind": "text",
      "reference": "book 232.1.2",
      "text": "ἐντέτασαι δ’ ὡς ἂν μήποτε παυσόμενον·",
      "witness_prefix": "",
      "speaker": null
    },
    {
      "kind": "text",
      "reference": "book 232.1.3",
      "text": "ἀλλ’ ὅτε μοι Νεμεσηνὸς ὅλον παρέκλινεν ἑαυτὸν",
      "witness_prefix": "",
      "speaker": null
    },
    {
      "kind": "text",
      "reference": "book 232.1.4",
      "text": "πάντα διδούς, ἃ θέλω, νεκρὸν ἀπεκρέμασο.",
      "witness_prefix": "",
      "speaker": null
    },
    {
      "kind": "text",
      "reference": "book 232.5",
      "text": "τείνεο καὶ ῥήσσου καὶ δάκρυε· πάντα ματαίως·",
      "witness_prefix": "",
      "speaker": null
    },
    {
      "kind": "text",
      "reference": "book 232",
      "text": "οὐχ ἕξεις ἔλεον χειρὸς ἀφ’ ἡμετέρης.",
      "witness_prefix": "",
      "speaker": null
    }
  ],
